his score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Class A","Class B","Class C","Class D","Class E"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Child-Pugh score is used to assess the prognosis of chronic liver disease and cirrhosis. It consists of five clinical measures: total bilirubin, serum albumin, prothrombin time/International Normalised Ratio, ascites, and hepatic encephalopathy. Each measure is scored 1-3 points, giving a total possible score of 5-15.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe scores are classified into three groups:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass A\u003C/strong\u003E: 5-6 points (mild disease)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass B\u003C/strong\u003E: 7-9 points (moderate disease)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass C\u003C/strong\u003E: 10-15 points (severe disease)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass D\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EClass E\u003C/strong\u003E do not exist in the Child-Pugh classification system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score of 8 falls within Class B, indicating moderate liver dysfunction with an estimated one-year survival rate of 80%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Child-Pugh score ranges from 5-15 points with three classes: A (5-6), B (7-9), and C (10-15) indicating increasing severity of liver dysfunction.","Child-Pugh B (7-9 points) indicates moderate liver dysfunction with 80% 1-year survival."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleine